  "prompt": "What is the average age of PhD graduates by discipline?",
  "response": "The average age of PhD graduates can vary significantly by discipline and country, as different fields may have varying lengths of study and professional experience required before entering a PhD program. Additionally, demographic factors and education systems influence average ages. Generally, PhD graduates tend to complete their programs between their late 20s and mid-30s across most disciplines.\n\nHere's a rough estimate of the average age of PhD graduates by some common disciplines:\n\n1. **Humanities and Social Sciences:** Around 33-35 years old. These disciplines often attract students who may have taken time off between undergraduate and graduate studies, or who may have gained professional experience before returning to academia.\n\n2. **Natural Sciences and Engineering:** Around 30-32 years old. These fields tend to have more direct paths from undergraduate to graduate studies, and students often enter PhD programs directly after completing their bachelor's or master's degrees.\n\n3. **Medicine and Health Sciences:** Around 34-37 years old. PhD students in these fields often already have professional degrees (like MDs) and may return to academia after gaining practical experience.\n\n4. **Business and Economics:** Around 31-33 years old. Similar to the natural sciences and engineering, there's often a direct path from undergraduate and master's programs, but these fields may also attract professionals who return to academia later in their careers.\n\nPlease note that these are general estimates and may vary based on factors like geographic region, specific academic programs, professional experience, and individual career paths. For precise data, it would be best to refer to studies and statistics specific to each discipline and region.",
